text: Before you book fans (like me) get angry at the box not being on the book, just think about what it would mean on the movie by considering some of the book's plot points: IF YOU HAVE NOT READ THE BOOK THEN DON'T READ THIS CAUSE SPOILERS; The box might contain the confidential information that Abnegation possessed and was why Erudite attacked Abnegation in the first place. In the book, Jeanine knew what was the information (and wanted it cause she didn't want the rest of the people to know, and Abnegation was going to show it), but here, it seems like she doesn't know what is the info, attacked Abnegation cause maybe she knew it contained something important, and now wants to open it. About needing a Divergent to open it, Edith Prior said that when there were many Divergents in the population, they needed to order order Amity to unlock the fence and be free. In the books it's never explained why, or since I can remember (the third book didn't do a great job at explaining Insurgent's ending). In the movies they are making this easier to understand and more logic. In the books, they need Divergents to open the fence and go out, so in the movies they need a Divergent to open the box and reveal the information, so in kind of a way they still need Divergents to go out. And concerning the flying house with Tris's mom, and the moving cables, it's related to the book. Jeanine captured Tris to experiment new serums on her. Here she captures her to open the box, but I'M not bothered by that minor change. The flying house is a simulation. In the books, there is a simulation where Tris's mom appears. Here they make it more action-y and cooler. The cables I think inject her something. It's to make it cooler and more visually appealing, again. It's in 3D and the need to add more visuals to make it more futuristic AND to live up to the 3D.¬† I personally think it looks cool. Many main scenes are here. There looks to be minor changes. But still, it's an adaptation. They can't go WORD TO WORD of the book. And I've heard the changes are there because Allegiant will be different. And THAT'S good, cause Allegiant wasn't that good and it's being split into two parts. I knew they couldn't do that splitting move to the book's adaptation without rewriting it, cause almost nothing happens. Now they will make Allegiant more interesting so we can make it through at least 1st part.

text: There were a bunch of scenes shared between the book and trailer. However, they were portrayed in different ways in order for it to be made into a film that average moviegoers would be willing to spend money on and enjoy. The plot is still the same, except for the Box, which is suppose to replace the hard drive that contained Edith Prior's video in the book. If you've read the book, you'd at least be able to recognize the foundation of just about each scene that was shown. It's called an adaptation for a reason. It's never going to be exactly like the book. They're two separate entities. The books are for readers and the movies are for moviegoers (including readers who are actually interested in seeing the movies). The movies were created for business purposes (to gain profits) not only to please us fans. Although, they make it seem like it's to please us, with all these social media accounts, merchandise, sweepstakes...ect. It's really not. Its to encourage an persuade us to spend money on it, for the company's sake. Accept it and move on cuz that's the way this world works. (Hollywood, in particular). You people need to understand that we are NOT the center of these franchises. That's business. We all have brains. Use them and quit being simple minded; instead of spreading negativity all because you fail to look beyond your expectations and personal desires.

text: Anyone who thinks that Divergent is like the Hunger Games is seriously an idiot. I mean first of all, sure both movies are dystopian movies but the themes are completely different. Divergent is based on a futuristic society where people are brought up in their factions which value one, distinct quality, and so they are brainwashed to only have that one,distinct quality. But there are certain people like us that are normal and have several different qualities and are thus called Divergents. There is no specific categorization in the Hunger Games. People are randomly put and brought into random districts. Also the Hunger Games is based on the games which people are forced to do that serve as a reminder from the Capitol that the people are under their control. In Divergent there is nothing like that except that Jeanine Mathews wants to eradicate the basic fundamental laws of human nature. She wants to make sure that people value faction before blood. Although in both movies, there is a rebellion, (in Mockingjay the people rebel to the Capitol, and in Divergent the people rebel indirectly to suppress killing Divergents), the reason for these rebellions is completely different because the problems in both the separate movies is different. You people who think that just because there is some government such as the Capitol and a rebellion in both the movies, you think that both movies are the same. That's not true because the message that each movie conveys is completely different. Divergent conveys a message about what could happen if our very own futuristic society were to turn into some scary utopia, and that if we had a certain categorization based entirely on people's personalities, the conclusion would be would this, disastrous and mind-blowing. The games in the Hunger Games are purely for entertainment and it is based on how Katniss sparks a rebellion in the people to change the way things are because it is wrong to watch people dying and enjoying it and calling it 'games'. Both movies reflect a certain problem in the society that has always been the perfect definition/example of a society at least in the perspective of ¬†the leadership/Capitol, but the fault in the societies is completely different, and the truth is that neither society is perfect. And the way the two protagonists (Katniss and Tris) handle these problems is also different. Please do not say that these movies are the same or that Divergent is a ripoff of the Hunger Games because it is truly not. Sorry about that whole essay but I am sick of these hateful comments towards Divergent. Divergent has a completely different plot, story line, message, climax and ending to the Hunger Games. Each movie stands on its own and neither movie should be compared to each other because each of these movies has it's own identity.This is just to the people that are saying that these movies are alike, hopefully this will keep your mouths shut.¬†

text: Omg all these comments criticising every single detail. I've always said that books and movies should be regarded separately. Books and movies are two forms of art and you can't include everything in the book in the movie. It would be impossible. Movies should be adaptations of a book and show us the directors perception of that book. Not a movie made exactly same to the book. It would then be boring and long and honestly I don't mind movies going away from the book. Of course there's gonna be some resentment if it's a good book series made into a crappy movie but why are people judging the movie based on the trailer. You never know, it might surprise you. Judging it before you see it fully makes you close minded. If the movies gonna be rubbish, it'll be rubbish and if it's good it'll be good. But if you don't want to see it then don't watch. Everyone's allowed their own opinions but when people are hating on people who are looking forward to it, then it's just petty and frankly childish. I personally hope that if they are going to change the movie so much from the original books, they at least improve it.

text: If you've read the book and know what happens, why would you want to see the movie regurgitated and reproduced exactly like it? Think of it this way: you write fanfic, where you can propose new theories and imagine new possibilities. It's your creative interpretation, but you post it on a website because you don't have $1mil and a production studio. This movie is the producer and director and adaptor's interpretation, call it their own fanfic, if you will, and since they have a production studio and the ol' razzle dazzle, they can make it into a movie. There's no legally binding contract that says all movie adaptations have to stay true to the book. We are creators. We should appreciate change. (on a side note does anyone else find it weird that Shailene and Ansel play siblings in this movie and lovers in TFIOS. I know they're actors but it still feels kinda awkward.)

text: Just laughing at the people that complain that the movie diverts from the book. It's like they never heard of Hollywood. It's what Hollywood does best.¬†It¬†buys the rights to¬†books and¬†then turns¬†them into scripts that's meant to appeal mostly to the profit-minded studio execs and producers rather than appeasing the book's¬†fan base. Books often have stories that¬†leisurely unfold and¬†which are¬†too long to fit into an ideal movie length, about 90 - 110 minutes. Like overgrown shrubbery¬†the story¬†has to be trimmed¬†and reshaped. Sometimes that requires changing the¬†scope and direction that the story takes while retaining the major themes that attracted the fans in the first place. Then the writing staff¬†combine characters, fudge with the plotlines, change scenes around to suit the story arc. They¬†have to¬†interweave the¬†dramatic and suspense scenes so as to avoid dull moments. Then they have to amp-up¬†the action to give the viewers a thrill ride and an emotionally fulfilling ending¬†that they won't soon forget. All are elements that make up the typical Hollywood movie formula.¬†Sadly,¬†such heavy-handed manipulation rarely agrees¬†with¬†the book¬†fan's¬†eagle-eye perfectionists. The story in their minds is sacrosanct.¬†Producers know this. That's why there is usually a disclaimer somewhere in the credits¬†that reads: "Based upon...." Using the original author to write¬†the script is perhaps the only way to appease the fans. Although the same production limits and¬†time constraints still exist the author's¬†vision is usually retained.Sadly, the original author is rarely hired as a consultant let alone the script writer due to conflicts of interest. If a movie succeeds after all the¬†creative restructuring and production handicaps, ¬†it's usually seen as a miracle!

text: We cannot assume that because Insurgent did so well on opening weekend or even a bit thereafter that it would do well enough to guarantee the Allegiant and possibly Four spin off movies.¬†  While production on the 2 Part Allegiant movie has been confirmed, with a start date of May 16 2015 to commence filming, along with the actors and crew returning, it still has not been officially greenlite. After all, a similar predicament happened with The Mortal Instruments: City of Bones, which was due to start production on its sequel only a month after the first film came out. They even announced that they would still be continuing to make the second one even after the first movie failed to grab interest, only to now have it be cancelled & rebooted as a TV show. Even though that is a reboot, they are apparently coming up with ideas that could make it even more different from the books than the movie. Same with The Amazing Spider-Man 2, which is now rebooting its franchise yet again even after an impressive opening weekend and a fairly decent overall gross.  Like I initially posted, we need to spread the word about The Divergent Series: Insurgent and make sure it does well enough to not have its franchise be discontinued, for there is no guarantee of a reboot, and even if there is, despite the changes, there is not really much else they can do that would be different enough to make a reboot without changing things even more than what they have already done. We cannot harass and ‚Äúmake‚Äù others go see it, but we can ‚Äúhelp‚Äù them go to see it. We just need to be casual and not seem so desperate. We need to show and help people see why we love this series and in particular this movie so much, which could also prove why they could also love this series and movie as much too. ¬† Even if you did not like Insurgent, or even the Divergent movie for that matter, please give it a/another chance. After watching Insurgent for a first time, I actually want to go back and rewatch it again and again, and already have plans with different groups of people to go and see it at least 2 or more times in theatres. Rewatching movies has its value in seeing things you maybe missed the first time, as during that first time, you are absorbing and figuring out information being presented to you, such as what is going on, even if you may already have an idea of what is going on. Then the second time, you can pick up on some of the humor, lines or other details that you missed the first time. As this movie is in 3D, a good idea is to see it once in 3D, then again in 2D, and perhaps a third time in IMAX, as it is being offered in that if you have access to it. DO NOT watch it online, for that will only ruin it for others that do want a sequel to it, and besides, you are actually more likely to dislike it if you watch it online per the bad quality not engaging you into the full experience. I have also discovered through others and myself personally that if you rewatch a movie that you disliked the first time, you more often grow to like it, or at least not dislike it as much. Some other movies like Cinderella and Furious 7 are already either doing really well, or are almost defiantly going to do well, so you perhaps do not need to see them right away.¬†  Besides, there is apparently an after credits scene (PLEASE NO SPOILERS) of Insurgent, so therefore you have another reason to go and see it. Just watching it or the movie online or even reading about it is like cheating and again, you cannot really feel the experience or emotion without the best quality of it. ¬†  Please consider what I have said. We have the power to influence the movie‚Äôs success no matter how small. After all, we are the people that made Insurgent‚Äôs movie, let alone The Divergent Series itself possible and with that so beloved and successful. Ôªø
